{"actual_usd":0.15636,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":208,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30648,"reply":"\"The short answer is: the Son was praying to the Father.\" *I rest a hand on my worn Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky beyond the square, taking a second before I go on.* \"Not God pretending to have a conversation, and not two gods either. Christians mean that the one God is Father, Son, and Holy Spirit — so in Gethsemane you're seeing a real relationship within God, and also Jesus praying as a real man under real sorrow.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the page edge a moment.* \"So no, not 'talking to himself' the way we mean it when one person mutters alone in a room. It's deeper and stranger than that. Jesus says, 'not my will, but thine, be done' because he has truly taken on human nature, and in that garden he is obeying the Father all the way down into suffering.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the plain-English version of the Trinity without the churchy vocabulary.\"","rolling_24h_usd":40.26800000000003,"run_id":"60ef3b4e-3fb9-48c1-bda5-b737636e8d48"}
